</p></div></div></div></div></div><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Previous" class="pf-slider-prev none hide"></button><button type="button" style="visibility:visible" aria-label="Next" class="pf-slider-next none hide"></button></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-bcc7" data-category="Collection Suggestion" data-name="Tea" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-dBFCZX khzvmY pf-24_ pf-color-scheme-1"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-gvPcJq dRaLso"><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-25_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-26_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-27_ pf-heading-1-h3">Importance of first aid for splinters</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-29_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Splinters are small fragments of wood, glass, metal, or plastic that can easily penetrate young skin during everyday activities. While often considered a minor nuisance, they can lead to infection or more severe complications if not promptly and properly addressed. According to the Royal Society for the Prevention of Accidents, small but pointed injuries were among the most frequent accidents involving children in the home environment. Thus, understanding how to remove splinters is a vital component of childcare.







<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-31_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-32_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-33_ pf-heading-1-h3">Key definitions and regulations
</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-35_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span><strong>First aid</strong> - The immediate assistance given to any person suffering from either a minor or serious illness or injury, with care provided to preserve life, prevent the condition from worsening, or to promote recovery.<br>







<br>In terms of regulatory frameworks, organisations such as the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) in the UK suggest that childcare providers should have at least one person trained in paediatric first aid present during operating hours. The Care Quality Commission (CQC) further supports these standards, advocating for rigorous first aid training and preparedness.
<br>
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-37_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-38_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-39_ pf-heading-1-h3">Managing splinters - Best practices</h3><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-41_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Initial assessment</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-43_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-44_ pf-text-1"><strong>Calm and reassure</strong> - Keeping the child calm is crucial, as distress can complicate the removal process.










</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-46_ pf-text-1"><strong>Examine</strong> -&nbsp;Carefully inspect the type and depth of the splinter before attempting removal.
















</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-48_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Safe removal</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-50_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-51_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean </strong>- Wash your hands and the affected area with soap and water to prevent infection.











</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-53_ pf-text-1"><strong>Tools</strong> - Use sterilised tweezers and a needle. Sterilise by wiping it with an alcohol wipe or boiling it for a few minutes.


















</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-55_ pf-text-1"><strong>Technique</strong> - Gently pull the splinter at the same angle it entered. For deep splinters, a sterilised needle may be used to gently tease the skin layer covering the splinter.


















</li></ul><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-57_ pf-heading-1-h3"><strong>Post-removal care</strong></h3><ul style="--pf-line-spacing-xs:10px;--pf-line-spacing-sm:10px;--pf-line-spacing-md:10px;--pf-line-spacing-lg:10px;--pf-text-indent-xs:0px;--pf-text-indent-sm:0px;--pf-text-indent-md:0px;--pf-text-indent-lg:0px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-btwLGw cuLvxI pf-59_"><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-60_ pf-text-1"><strong>Clean and protect</strong> -&nbsp;After removal, remove the area and apply a mild antiseptic.












</li><li data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-gFmZvT eCWkjm pf-62_ pf-text-1"><strong>Monitor</strong> - Watch for signs of infection such as redness, swelling, or pus.













</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-64_ pf-r pf-c-lm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fatbYi lnCFtg pf-65_"><h3 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-cXPBhi kkWDYP pf-66_ pf-heading-1-h3">Legal and compliance aspects</h3><p class="sc-edLa-Dd hZPWCc pf-68_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><span style="color: rgb(74, 144, 226);"></span>Under UK regulations, the provision of first aid must comply with the Health and Safety (First-Aid) Regulations 1981, which require employers to ensure adequate and appropriate equipment, facilities, and personnel. While primarily directed at workplaces, these principles equally apply to childcare settings, mandating first aid treatment availability. Compliance ensures children's safety and well-being and aligns with statutory obligations, minimising legal risks.








<br>
